<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In typography, characters set in a smaller point size and positioned above the <a title="Baseline" href="Baseline">baseline</a>, also called a <a title="Superscript" href="Superscript">superscript</a>. Superior characters are used for exponents (such as "10<sup>13</sup>"), <a title="Footnote" href="Footnote">footnote</a>s ("<sup>2</sup>See <em>The GATF Encyclopedia of Graphic Communication</em>...."), etc. They are most often numerals, but letters can be used as well. Superiors can be "manufactured" by changing to a smaller size and advancing the line spacing (if this capability is available) for positioning. See also <a title="Inferior" href="Inferior">Inferior</a>. 
</p>
